      • setStock

        public void setStock(Stock stock)
        Set the stock that is being used in this transaction. NOTE: the stock needs to already have downloaded its values, or else this operation will take place with outdated data, or possibly not even have the necessary data at all.

        This class will only accept an OwnedStock as a parameter, because only a stock that is owned and has a quantity value can have shares be sold. If the parameter is not an OwnedStock, an exception is thrown.

        Overrides:
        setStock in class TransactionDialog
        Parameters:
        stock - the stock that is being used in this transaction.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the stock parameter is not an instance of OwnedStock.

      • limitValueText

        Description copied from class: TransactionDialog
        This method should return text representing the value of the maximum limit on the number of shares that can be a part of this transaction. This value does not have to be an actual number of shares, it can be any value that has the effect of restricting the number of shares.
        Specified by:

      • getValueForAction

        public java.lang.Object getValueForAction(java.lang.String valueToGet)
        Description copied from interface: ListenerView
        Returns a value from the view that is needed to perform a given action. The actionCommand parameter passed here determines which, if any, value will be returned. If no value is needed for a particular action, simply return null.

        THREAD SAFETY: Again, this is a Swing class. Controllers that off-load their tasks to other threads need to make sure that they only call on this method on the EventDispatchThread.

        Parameters:
        valueToGet - the action command for the action being performed, to determine which, if any, values are needed from this view.
        Returns:
        the value needed for the specified action, or null if no value is needed.
